author: @muhammadabdullahdilshad8509
text: Notes Section  # Dictioneries  # Allows us to work with the Key value Pair # Associatobe to the hashmaps  # We have keys and the corresponding Value   student  = {'john':'player','Age':22,'courses': ['Maths','Compsci']} print(student)  #Also we can specify the key to see the value of the key print(student['courses'])# While accessing the key value that does not exist It returns a error # It can also be done thrugh the get method print (student.get('john')) #In this case it will return none if the key is not present #We can also set an alt tect if the key is not found in the dictionery print(student.get('phone','Not Found'))   #Add a new Entry into the Dictionery student['phone'] = '555-555-555' print(student)  #To update the value  student['Age'] = 25 print(student)   #To update multiple key valeus at once student.update({'john':'Random','Age':27}) print(student)   #To delete Dictonery Entry we do del student['Age'] print(student)  #We can also store the deleted value in some Variable name  = student.pop('john') print(name)  #To see all the keys print(student.keys())  #To see the lenght of thr dict print(len(student))   #To see all the values print(student.values())  #to see the keys and the value  print(student.items())  #To loop throgh the Dict for keys in student:     print(keys)  #To get the Key and the values we can use the items method for keys,values in student.items():     print(keys,values)

author: @MarkSudduth1
text: There is a slight inaccuracy in something you said around the 2 minute mark.  You said that a key is any immutable data type and technically this statement is not wrong, but it implies that keys can ONLY be an immutable data type, which is inaccurate.  There are mutable data types that can be keys.  It would have been more accurate to say keys MUST be a hashable data type.  All immutable objects are hashable but not all hashable objects are immutable, an example of a mutable object that is hashable is a user defined class object.  There is also the curious case of the tuple data type.  Tuples are an immutable and should therefore be hashable, but if a tuple contains a mutable data type such as a list, then it will no longer be hashable, therefore could not be used as a key.  And it gets even weirder because an unhashable  tuple still has a __hash__ attribute.  So its like some kind of transvestite data type that hasn't completely transitioned, lol. Anyway, this is all very pedantic and probably not very helpful to your audience.  Your video is very well done.

author: @1cannon3
text: 0:07 ‚Äì Terminology 0:14 ‚Äì Key/Value pairs definition 0:37 - First example (Student using a dictionary) 0:45 ‚Äì { }, Dict notation, curly braces,  0:50 ‚Äì adding elements 1:32 ‚Äì [ ] Square bracket access of the dict 2:04 ‚Äì Dict items can be many things, they‚Äôre not bound to one ‚Äútype‚Äù 2:14 ‚Äì Keys can be any immutable data type 2:24 ‚Äì Example of an Integer being the key 2:44 ‚Äì Accessing a key that does not exist 3:00 ‚Äì Alternative to ‚Äúthrowing an error‚Äù if a key does not exist 3:05 ‚Äì Sometimes you will want to return None or a default value if key does not exist 3:09 - .get( ) access of the dict 3:30 ‚Äì accessing a key that does not exist with the .get method as opposed to [ ] square bracket access 3:40 ‚Äì Specifying a default value for keys that do not exist 4:01 ‚Äì Adding a new entry to dictionary 4:30 ‚Äì Changing/updating values via key access 5:02 ‚Äì Changing/updating values via .update() method 5:21 - .update() takes in a dict as an argument 5:57 ‚Äì Deleting a specific key and its value 6:01 ‚Äì Option 1 for deleting a key and value: del keyword 6:26 ‚Äì Option 2 for removing a key and value: .pop() method 6:30 ‚Äì Remember the .pop() method not only removes the item put pops it off or returns it to you 6:35 ‚Äì Therefore you can recover the popped item with a variable assignment 7:07 ‚Äì How to loop through all the keys and values 7:13 ‚Äì Finding out the number of keys in dict with len() function 7:30 ‚Äì Print all keys with .keys() method 7:39 ‚Äì Print all values with .values() method 7:47 ‚Äì Print both keys and values with .items() method 8:07 ‚Äì Looping is slightly different then lists because dicts are concerned with pairs (Key : Value) 8:33 ‚Äì How to loop through keys AND values

author: @alessandroanderson9094
text: student = {'name':'John','age':25,'courses':['math','CompSci']}  print (student) # {'name':'John','age':25,'courses':['math','CompSci']}  print(student['courses']) # ['math', 'CompSci']  try:     print(student['phone']) # KeyError: 'phone' except:     None   print (student.get('age'))    # 25 print (student.get('phone'))  # None print (student.get('phone','Not Found'))  # Not Found  student['phone'] = '555-555' # creates new key print (student) # {'name': 'John', 'age': 25, 'courses': ['math', 'CompSci'], 'phone': '555-555'}  student['name'] = 'Alex' # the value 'John is updated to 'Alex' print (student) # {'name': 'Alex', 'age': 25, 'courses': ['math', 'CompSci'], 'phone': '555-555'}  student.update({'name':'Mike', 'age':29,'phone':'111-111'}) # update more than one in one row print (student) # {'name': 'Mike', 'age': 29, 'courses': ['math', 'CompSci'], 'phone': '111-111'}  del student['age'] # deleates pair print (student) # {'name': 'Mike', 'courses': ['math', 'CompSci'], 'phone': '111-111'}  phone = student.pop('phone') # phone = '111-111' # grab removed vale w/ a variableprint (student) print(phone) # phone = '111-111' print (student) # {'name': 'Mike', 'courses': ['math', 'CompSci']}  a = student.values() print(a) # dict_values(['Mike', ['math', 'CompSci']])  a = student.keys() print(a) # dict_keys(['name', 'courses'])  a = student.items() print(a) # dict_items([('name', 'Mike'), ('courses', ['math', 'CompSci'])])   for x in student: # Normal looping will onlyi terate keys:     print(x)  for k,v in student.items():      print(k,v)
